      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize if the previous response felt too chaotic. I can certainly explain the retail math clearly and directly.\n\nTo calculate your **Inventory Turnover Ratio**, you divide your **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)** by your **Average Inventory Value**.\n\nThe formula is:\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\nRegarding your second question, a **low inventory turnover ratio** indicates that you are not selling your stock quickly enough. Specifically for your cash flow, the risks include:\n\n1.  **Tied-Up Capital:** Money that should be sitting in your bank account as cash is instead locked up in unsold inventory. You can't use this capital for rent, payroll, or marketing.\n2.  **Increased Storage Costs:** Holding onto clothes longer means paying more for warehouse space, utilities, and insurance.\n3.  **Obsolescence Risk:** In the fashion industry, trends change rapidly. If items sit too long, they may go out of style or become damaged, forcing you to write them off as a loss rather than selling them at a profit.\n4.  **Missed",
